\begin_layout Solution
Let's first simplify the linear system.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \left\{ \begin{array}{rcrcrlr}
x & + & y & - & z & = & -2\\
3x & - & 5y & + & 13z & = & 18\\
x & - & 2y & + & 5z & = & k
\end{array}\right.\\
\begin{array}{c}
\\L_{2}-3L_{1}\\
L_{3}-L_{1}
\end{array} & \left\{ \begin{array}{rcrcrlr}
x & + & y & - & z & = & -2\\
0 & - & 8y & + & 16z & = & 24\\
0 & - & 3y & + & 6z & = & k+2
\end{array}\right.\\
\begin{array}{c}
\\-\tfrac{1}{8}L_{2}\\
-\tfrac{1}{3}L_{3}
\end{array} & \left\{ \begin{array}{rcrcrlr}
x & + & y & - & z & = & -2\\
0 & + & y & - & 2z & = & -3\\
0 & + & y & - & 2z & = & -\frac{k+2}{3}
\end{array}\right.\\
\begin{array}{c}
\\\\L_{3}-L_{2}
\end{array} & \left\{ \begin{array}{rcrcrlr}
x & + & y & - & z & = & -2\\
0 & + & y & - & 2z & = & -3\\
0 & + & 0 & + & 0 & = & 3-\frac{k+2}{3}
\end{array}\right.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Since our last equation is 
\begin_inset Formula $0=3-\frac{k+2}{3}$
\end_inset

,
 the only value for 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 for which this system has any solutions is the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 that makes this last equation true,
 which is 
\begin_inset Formula $k=7$
\end_inset

.
 For every other value of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 there are no solutions.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $k=7$
\end_inset

 there exist infinitely many solutions because we can set 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 equal to any value and then solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 This solves part (a) and part (b).
 We now solve part (c):
 We set 
\begin_inset Formula $k=7$
\end_inset

,
 getting the system of equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ \begin{array}{rcrcrlr}
x & + & y & - & z & = & -2\\
0 & + & y & - & 2z & = & -3\\
0 & + & 0 & + & 0 & = & 0
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset

To find the solutions,
 we set 
\begin_inset Formula $z=t$
\end_inset

,
 an arbitrary number,
 and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

,
 getting 
\begin_inset Formula $y=-3+2t$
\end_inset

,
 and solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 getting 
\begin_inset Formula $x=-2+t-(-3+2t)$
\end_inset

,
 or simplifying:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{cases}
x=1-t\\
y=-3+2t\\
z=t
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

